04269nam a22006135i 9780292749214DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20211966txu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802927492147 a10.7560/7361152doi  a(DE-B1597)588693  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  atxucUS-TX 7aBIO0020002bisacsh1 aDale, Edward Everett, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Cross Timbers :bMemories of a North Texas Boyhood /cEdward Everett Dale. 1aAustin : bUniversity of Texas Press, c[2021] 4c©1966  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Be It Ever So Humble -- t2. Neighbors and Visitors -- t3. Vittles: Plain and Fancy -- t4. Reading: Common and Preferred -- t5. "Six Days Shalt Thou Labor" -- t6. Play and Playmates -- t7. Young Nimrods -- t8. Disciples of St. Peter and Izaak Walton -- t9. School and Schoolmates -- t10. Cross Timbers Society -- t11. The Lure of the West -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe activities of a young boy on a small farm in the Texas Cross Timbers during the 1880s seem especially distant today. No one can remember the adventure of a sixteen-and-a-half-mile journey, which consumed the greater part of a day; or hurried predawn dressing in a frosty cold loft while the fragrance of a hearty breakfast wafted upward through the floor cracks; or a two-room schoolhouse, where the last half of Friday afternoon was given over to “speaking pieces” or to spelling and ciphering matches. Through the recollections of Edward Everett Dale we are able to view a pattern of life in rural America now gone forever. For The Cross Timbers is a story which, with but a few minor variations, could have been told about a vast number of small boys on farms cleared from the virgin forests in the timbered regions of many states. After presenting a brief introduction to the members of the Dale family and the plant, animal, and bird life of the Lower Cross Timbers countryside, the author describes his boyhood of a past century. He tells of his home, its furnishings, and the food served there, as well as the neighbors and relatives who come to visit. We learn of the superstitions, the humorous homespun expressions, the mores of early rural Texans. We hunt and fish with young Master Dale in the thick woods and along the clear creeks. Pioneer life demanded much hard work, but not to the exclusion of a diverting social life—both of which included the youngsters, as the author so graphically relates. Dale tells us also of the religious and secular education of the era, showing the significance of the home in supplementing these two influences. Anyone reading this volume must be impressed by the great differences in the lifeways of rural children today and of those of the end of the nineteenth century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Cultural Heritage.2bisacsh1 aBiggers, John.40uhttps://doi.org/10.7560/73611540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292749214423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292749214/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK